posts.raw_content:
As Christmas approaches, I find myself drawn to the quieter aspects of the story that the world often overlooks.

Before the advent of crowns, kingdoms, churches, and traditions, there was a young woman who accepted God’s call without comprehending the unfolding events. There was a man who chose faith over fear. There was a child born not into power or comfort, but into humility. No palaces, no armies, just obedience, trust, and love.

“And the Word became flesh and dwelt among us.”

That’s the miracle we’re about to witness once again this season.

It’s easy to feel disheartened right now. The world seems loud, fractured, and unstable. Trolls and stormfags abound, and truth is often mocked. Faith is treated like a relic, conviction is labeled cruelty, and humility is mistaken for weakness. However, Christmas reminds us that God accomplishes His greatest work in unexpected places, through ordinary individuals, in moments that may appear insignificant at the time.

Christ didn’t come to validate the world as it was. He came to redeem it.

He didn’t arrive with force but through sacrifice. He didn’t seek to rule through fear but to save through love. This doesn’t mean truth became weaker; it means it became flesh—lived, walked out among us.

This season calls us back to that example.

We must stand firm without becoming cruel. We must speak truth without losing compassion. We must hold our ground while remembering the significance of that ground.

Christmas is not about escaping hardship; it’s about God joining us in it.

So, if things feel broken, weary, or confusing, you’re closer to the manger than you realize.

Take time this season to be still, pray, read the story again, spend time with your family, extend grace wherever possible, and remember that light shines brightest in the darkness not because the darkness is powerful, but because it cannot overpower the light.

“Glory to God in the highest, and on earth peace, good will toward men.”

May that peace rest on your homes, your hearts, and your faith this Christmas.

I apologize for my preaching tone, but I genuinely wish you all a very Merry Christmas.

Merry Christmas
